## **`Overview`**

`The Entity-Relationship (ER) Model is designed to integrate and structure data from the Global Financial Development Database, Doing Business Database, and World Development Indicators within a relational database. This model ensures efficient data storage, minimizes redundancy, and supports complex financial, business, and economic analyses through optimized queries.`

## 

## 

## **`Entities and Attributes`**

### **`1. Country`**

`Represents nations included in the database.`

* **`Primary Key (PK):`** `Country_Code`  
* **`Attributes:`**  
  * `Country_Code (VARCHAR, Unique) – Unique identifier for each country.`  
  * `Country_Name (VARCHAR) – Official name of the country.`

### **`2. Indicator`**

`Stores details about various financial, business, and economic indicators.`

* **`Primary Key (PK):`** `Series_Code`  
* **`Attributes:`**  
  * `Series_Code (VARCHAR, Unique) – Unique identifier for each indicator.`  
  * `Series_Name (VARCHAR) – Descriptive name of the indicator.`

### **`3. Financial Data (Associative Entity)`**

`Serves as a bridge table that connects Country and Indicator with time-series values.`

* **`Composite Primary Key (PK):`** `(Country_Code, Series_Code, Year)`  
* **`Foreign Keys (FK):`**  
  * `Country_Code → Country (Country_Code)`  
  * `Series_Code → Indicator (Series_Code)`  
* **`Attributes:`**  
  * `Country_Code (VARCHAR, FK) – References the associated country.`  
  * `Series_Code (VARCHAR, FK) – References the measured indicator.`  
  * `Year (INTEGER) – The year in which the data was collected.`  
  * `Value (FLOAT) – The numerical value of the indicator for the specified country and year.`

## **`Relationships`**

### **`1. Many-to-Many Relationship Between Country and Indicator`**

* `A Country can have multiple indicators recorded over time.`  
* `An Indicator can be measured across multiple countries.`  
* **`Resolution:`** `This many-to-many relationship is managed by the Financial Data table, which serves as an associative entity linking countries and indicators over time.`

### **`2. Relationship Between Country and Financial Data`**

* **`Optional One-to-Many:`**  
  * `A Country may or may not have financial data recorded.`  
  * `However, every Financial Data record must belong to a Country.`

### **`3. Relationship Between Financial Data and Indicator`**

* **`Optional One-to-Many:`**  
  * `An Indicator may or may not have financial data recorded.`  
  * `However, every Financial Data record must be associated with an Indicator.`
